@ThinkingandTinkering On a mass scale as a passive permanent installation it makes a lot of sense since it makes otherwise 'useless' areas into power generation systems without the cost or the visual clutter of traditional solar collectors, even though the known reduction in overall efficiency.

Arguably, the difference in efficiency could be deemed less than with traditional solar since plants do not need to be facing the sun at a specific angle to work, and can work in lower light than panels, so instead of being 10,000:1 it might only be like 5,000:1 [just throwing the numbers out there for 'example' and not trying to say how much the difference really is] because these tiny little plants require no motors to steer them and do not need to be washed or inspected for cracks, and storm related damage is probably negligible.

Granted, a direct strike from lightning might be pretty devastating...but that is not really super likely and it might only do localized damage in the end.
